      <p>No, I&#39;m totally with you on the digestive biscuit thing! And I&#39;m also American! I always have a couple with my tea (which usually occurs a couple of hours after lunch). It&#39;s that fabulous whole wheat-y taste! Can&#39;t wait to try these. Glad I stumbled on your blog.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="reply">
      <a rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='#comment-21007' data-commentid="21007" data-postid="690" data-belowelement="comment-21007" data-respondelement="respond" data-replyto="Reply to indirectlibre" aria-label='Reply to indirectlibre'>Reply</a>    </div>
  </li><!-- #comment-## -->
  <li id="comment-53702" class="comment even thread-even depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn">Meg</cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2010/11/i-am-sold/#comment-53702"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2016-05-10T22:15:04-04:00">Tuesday, May 10, 2016 at 10:15 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>I&#8217;ve made these tons of times and love them. Tonight tried them with 2c spelt flour and 1 c white flour, and replaced the brown sugar with coconut sugar. SO GOOD! I would do the same variation again. Perfect texture.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="reply">
      <a rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='#comment-53702' data-commentid="53702" data-postid="690" data-belowelement="comment-53702" data-respondelement="respond" data-replyto="Reply to Meg" aria-label='Reply to Meg'>Reply</a>    </div>
  </li><!-- #comment-## -->
  <li id="comment-67233" class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="http://www.f1cookbook.com" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">Maria</a></cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2010/11/i-am-sold/#comment-67233"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2017-10-03T17:41:38-04:00">Tuesday, October 3, 2017 at 5:41 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>I was gathering a list of my favorite recipes from my favorite blogs recently, and this was the first on the list. 1. Because they are so delicious and feel so homey and I have loved them for years now. And almost as importantly 2. Because you Molly, are an inspiration. I love reading your writing, I love your photography and I laugh weekly to you and Matthew on Spilled Milk. Thank you for everything. Keep living the good life!</p>
    </div>

    <div class="reply">
      <a rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='#comment-67233' data-commentid="67233" data-postid="690" data-belowelement="comment-67233" data-respondelement="respond" data-replyto="Reply to Maria" aria-label='Reply to Maria'>Reply</a>    </div>
  </li><!-- #comment-## -->
  <li id="comment-99243" class="comment even thread-even depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn">P</cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2010/11/i-am-sold/#comment-99243"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2022-03-19T17:37:36-04:00">Saturday, March 19, 2022 at 5:37 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>I&#8217;m currently at my sister&#8217;s and every time  I come over I try to bake something because I know how much they appreciate it since they&#8217;re no bakers.  This afternoon I woke up from a nap and went straight to the kitchen. I found 2 bags of chocolate chips so I thought  why not cookies.. It&#8217;s  a huge batch but I&#8217;m glad I did not make half of it because they will be gone soon  . the last time I was here I made your graham crackers . A hit , both times.<br />
 Cooking is love in my books</p>
    </div>

    <div class="reply">
      <a rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='#comment-99243' data-commentid="99243" data-postid="690" data-belowelement="comment-99243" data-respondelement="respond" data-replyto="Reply to P" aria-label='Reply to P'>Reply</a>    </div>
  </li><!-- #comment-## -->
    </ol>

      
  
